During deformation at 1200 , the yield strengths of HfMo 0.5 NbTiV 0.5 and HfMo 0.5 NbTiV 0.5 Si 0.7 alloys are 60MPa and 235MPa, respectively

For the matrix HfMo 0.5 NbTiV 0.5 alloy, the hardness is 403 HV. Si addition has a promoting effect on the hardness increase. Evidently, the formation of silicide strengthens the matrix. When the content of Si is 0.7, the hardness reaches 612 HV. Meanwhile, the values of hardness have large fluctuations with the formation of the silicide because of the major difference in hardness between the matrix and silicide, as well as the non-uniform distribution of silicide in the microscopic area. The matrix HfMo 0.5 NbTiV 0.5 alloy has the maximum compressive plasticity of 35% without fracture, and the yield strength is 1260MPa. However, the HfMo 0.5 NbTiV 0.7 alloy has the maximum yield strength (as high as 2134MPa) while still exhibiting a fracture strain of 9.2%.
the respective yield strength and fracture strain of the HfMo 0.5 NbTiV 0.5 alloy were 35% and 1260MPa
the yield strength and fracture strain of the HfMo 0.5 NbTiV 0.5 Si 0.7 alloy were 9.2% and 2134MPa

The yield strengths of HfMo 0.5 NbTiV 0.5 and HfMo 0.5 NbTiV 0.5 Si 0.7 alloys were 60MPa and 235MPa at 1200 , respectively. The attractive strength at elevated temperatures of the Si-containing alloys was strongly dependent on the strengthening effect caused by the silicides.
